A process is a running program, like an app or a script. When multiple processes are running, Linux assumes the ones using the most CPU or memory are the most important, but thatâ€™s not always the case. To manage this, Linux provides several commands for viewing, controlling, and prioritizing processes.

->>Viewing Processes
ps aux â€“> View all running processes
ps -u username â€“> View processes for a specific user
ps -C processname â€“> Show a process by name
pgrep processname â€“> Find a process by name and get its PID
pidof processname â€“> Find the PID of a running program

->>Managing Processes
kill PID â€“> Terminate a process by its PID
pkill processname â€“> Terminate a process by name
kill -9 PID â€“> Force kill a process
pkill -9 processname â€“> Kill all instances of a process
kill -STOP PID â€“> Stop a running process
kill -CONT PID â€“> Resume a stopped process
renice -n 10 -p PID â€“> Lower priority of a process
renice -n -5 -p PID â€“> Increase priority (requires root access)

->>Background & Foreground Processes
command & â€“> Run a command in the background
jobs â€“> List background jobs
fg %jobnumber â€“> Bring a job to the foreground
Ctrl + Z â€“> Suspend a running process
bg %jobnumber â€“> Resume a suspended process in the background

->>Daemon Process Management
systemctl list-units --type=service â€“> List system services (daemons)
systemctl start service-name â€“> Start a service
systemctl stop service-name â€“> Stop a service
systemctl enable service-name â€“> Enable a service at startup

The important takeaway is how nice and renice commands help me control the priority of processes. A lower nice value means a higher priority, and a higher nice value means a lower priority.

